  "doc_id": "39502",
  "text": "Interestingly, this response is specific to the brain microenvironment. In the lung, copper levels are far higher and C. neoformans instead faces a different challenge and needs to upregulate metallothioneins to counteract potential copper-mediated toxicity [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Whether copper restriction in the brain is a deliberate method of preventing infection or a self-preserving mechanism to prevent damage to neurons is not well understood. Further study into these mechanisms of 'nutritional immunity' is likely to yield promising new insights into how trace metals provide organ-specific immune responses to control infection, and may provide further clarity into how copper acquisition by C. neoformans could be targeted to prevent CM.",
